<p><div class="left-margin" id="set-A"><h2>Before the Main Article</h2></div></p>
<p>I had a fun time with cold steel series. The character interaction is so far good, except the bond events. However, I find the main story strange after reaching the end of the cold steel series, including gameplay experience in Hajimari-no-kiseki. I do not watch through all bond events of each character, so the article mentions the observation to main story only.
<br /><br /></p>

<p><div class="left-margin" id="set-B"><h2>Strange Points in Main Story</h2></div></p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Olivert in “Trails in the sky 3rd” vs “Trails of Cold Steel”</strong></p>

    <p>You may review the conversation between Olivert and Osborne.</p>

    <iframe class="center" width="100%" height="400" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Jxdq4mI46kY" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>

    <p>Osborne is apparently an opponent of Olivert. However, Olivert does not have much significant actions to take down him during cold steel series. He kinda leave the confrontation to Rean, and turns into a support role.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Build a new class to enforce better culture to empire?</strong></p>

    <p>I know his intention to improve the current social culture of the empire, but the education should be a long term enforcement, instead of having immediate result. Students do need time to climb into higher positions in the society, for them to change the social ideologies or policies.</p>

    <p>The older generations are the ones to rule the society, and the younger generations may need to endure some injustice. If the social culture can be change as easy as just building a new class, I don’t think there need several games to explain the things.</p>

    <p>There is an exception like Crossbell. It faces serious crisis, so everyone needs to change for suvivor. However, main characters in cold steel face crisis while there is a lot of helps, so it seems not applicable.</p>

    <p>I don’t mean the age matter in the policy enforcement. The older generations have their wisdom in their lives and they do contribute to make a society operating well. The younger generations may have their insights to make society, or every individual living better. In short, the personality and moral standard matter, rather than age. Please do not bind age groups into stereotypes~~</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Reinford is left barely mentioned.</strong></p>

    <p>Reinford is a manufaturer of military weapons. For such a large company, with a lot of earning from military, the incident should not be tackled by only changing the direction of the company. How the monetary flow goes? What responsbilities should they bear? The main story does not mention much, and the detailed descriptions seem to be skipped intentionally. All the Reinford related members mention their company with few words, and seem nothing happened.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Divine Knight in Nord Highlands</strong></p>

    <p>Stone statues can be observed in Nord Highlands, with unused Divine Knight(s).</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Find a Divine Knight in the school by accident</strong></p>

    <p>How come a old schoolhouse has a unused Divine Knight, and the main protagonist Rean accidentally become its pliot? This kind of story seems like everything going by accident, such like the character development of Rean…</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Make acquaintance to some characters in a weird way.</strong></p>

    <p>For example, Vita suddenly make acquaintance to Rean. Although it may be interpreted that Rean is an important person to Osborne, it still look quite strange without proper follow-up in later story.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Conflicts between nobels and commoners</strong></p>

    <p>This should be an important topic in Erebonian Empire. The different social classes influence their rights. This should be one of the reason for Osborne gaining advocation from commoners. Cold steel 1 mentions the conflicts between class VII and nobel members, but the descriptions are quite few. It looks like the arguments between immature students, instead of having great impact to the general lives in Erebonian Empire.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

